      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A mother brings her 8-year-old boy with complaints of joint pain and backache. The mother reports a history of hypermobility and frequent dislocations of his shoulders and knees. She also mentions the family history of heart problems in her Husband. Upon further examination, a lens dislocation is identified. A diagnosis of a Fibrillin protein defect was identified. What is the most common cardiac condition that can be seen in this boy? </span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4697829",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32706,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) Mitral Valve Prolapse</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Marfan syndrome is a genetic disorder </strong>affecting<strong> connective tissue</strong>, and it is known to have <strong>several cardiovascular manifestations </strong>due to the<strong> weakness in the connective tissue</strong>.<strong> Mitral valve prolapse is the most common cardiac condition seen in individuals with Marfan syndrome</strong>. It occurs due to the <strong>enlargement and redundancy of the mitral valve leaflets</strong>, which can lead to <strong>mitral regurgitation.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Patients have to be<strong> managed with regular echocardiography </strong>to detect <strong>if cardiac surgery is required</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>The operations </strong>can be <strong>delayed by the use of &szlig;-blocker medication or angiotensin receptor-2 blockers</strong>, to keep <strong>the blood pressure as low as reasonable</strong>. <strong>Neonatal Marfan syndrome is particularly severe</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Atrial Septal Defect</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - While atrial septal defects can be a<strong> part of the spectrum of congenital heart diseases, they are not specifically associated with Marfan syndrome</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Ventricular Septal Defect</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - Similar to atrial septal defects, <strong>VSDs are not the most common cardiac manifestation in Marfan syndrome.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Mitral Stenosis</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - This condition involves <strong>narrowing of the mitral valve and is not typically associated with Marfan syndrome.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Marfan syndrome: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Heart defects includes:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Aortic root dilatation (may rupture in later teenage life)</span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Aortic regurgitation</span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Mitral valve prolapse</span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Mitral regurgitation</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Associated defects:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><em>FBN1 </em>gene mutation on chromosome 15, or <em>TGFBR2 </em>mutation</span></span></strong></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Dural ectasia</span></span></strong></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">High arched palate</span></span></strong></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Arm-span greater than height</span></span></strong></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Hypermobility</span></span></strong></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Lens dislocation (</strong>Superolateral)</span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Pectus excavatum</span></span></strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: <strong>Nelson 20<sup>th</sup> Edition, Page No. 618-619 and 644-645</strong></span></span></span></p>",
